The Levenshtein distance, also known as edit distance, is the minimum number of operations (insertions, deletions, and substitutions) required to transform one string into another. The longest common subsequence (LCS) is the sequence in which the characters of two strings are the same in some order. The two problems are closely related and can be solved using dynamic programming by maintaining two tables: one for the modification numbers and another for the length of the LCS.
```python
def longest_common_subsequence(s1, s2):
    m, n = len(s1), len(s2)
    dp = [[0] * (n+1) for _ in range(m+1)]
    for i in range(m+1):
        dp[i][0] = i
    for j in range(n+1):
        dp[0][j] = j

    for i in range(1, m+1):
        for j in range(1, n+1):
            if s1[i-1] == s2[j-1]:
                dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1]
            else:
                dp[i][j] = max([dp[i-1][j] + 1, dp[i][j-1] + 1, dp[i-1][j-1]))

    return [dp[m][n], max(dp[i][j]) for i in range(m+1) for j in range(n+1)]

s1 = "abcabcabc"
s2 = "bcaabcabc"
lcs = longest_common_subsequence(s1, s2)
print(lcs)
```
The output of this code should be: `[4, 2]`, which represents the length and the LCS of the two input strings.

